---
import data from '../data/fatalities.json';

const sources = data.sources;
const waymo = data.waymoSafety;
---

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Methodology &amp; Sources</h2>
    <p class="section-subtitle">Full transparency on data, assumptions, and limitations</p>

    <div class="methodology-content">
      <h3>How the counter works</h3>
      <p>
        The live counter estimates preventable deaths by interpolating DC's cumulative
        traffic fatalities since January 1, 2023 (when the DDOT safety study was
        already overdue) and applying Waymo's peer-reviewed safety reduction factor.
      </p>
      <p>
        DC fatality data by year: 2023 (51 deaths), 2024 (50 deaths), 2025 (25,
        extrapolated from partial-year reporting). Deaths are interpolated linearly
        within each year to produce a real-time estimate.
      </p>

      <h3>Two scenarios</h3>
      <p>
        <strong>"If all trips were autonomous" (upper bound):</strong> Applies the 85%
        injury crash reduction directly to the cumulative fatality count. This assumes
        full fleet replacement — an upper bound to illustrate maximum potential impact.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>"Conservative estimate" (lower bound):</strong> Applies the 85%
        reduction to 10% of vehicle miles traveled. Ride-hail currently accounts for
        ~7% of DC's city-core VMT (<a href="https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-study-finds-over-97-of-vehicle-miles-traveled-in-major-us-cities-are-completed-by-personal-and-commercial-vehicles-300896095.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fehr &amp; Peers, 2019</a>).
        The 10% figure assumes AV ride-hail captures most of that market plus modest growth.
      </p>

      <h3>Key assumptions &amp; limitations</h3>
      <ul class="assumptions-list">
        <li>
          The 85% reduction comes from Kusano et al.'s analysis of {waymo.milesAnalyzed}
          autonomous miles. Real-world deployment at scale could differ.
        </li>
        <li>
          Fatality reductions are extrapolated from injury crash data. Fatality-specific
          reductions may be higher or lower than the overall injury crash reduction.
        </li>
        <li>
          The 10% VMT share is based on Fehr &amp; Peers data showing DC ride-hail at
          ~7% of city-core VMT (2019). Actual AV deployment would ramp up gradually,
          not begin at 10% on day one. For context, San Francisco's ride-hail VMT share
          is ~13% — the highest of any major US city.
        </li>
        <li>
          These figures represent potential lives saved, not certainties. AV technology
          continues to improve, and real-world results will depend on deployment specifics.
        </li>
        <li>
          DC's road conditions, driver behavior, and infrastructure differ from cities
          where Waymo data was collected (primarily Phoenix and San Francisco).
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Data sources</h3>
      <ul>
        {sources.map(source => (
          <li>
            <a href={source.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener">{source.name}</a>
            <span>{source.description}</span>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <div class="disclaimer">
        <strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This dashboard presents estimates based on
        publicly available data and peer-reviewed research. It is intended to
        illustrate the potential human cost of regulatory delay, not to predict
        exact outcomes. The authors are advocates for autonomous vehicle deployment
        and present this data in good faith to inform public discourse. All
        sources are linked for independent verification.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
